JavaScript Proxy:

 
- A Proxy is a JavaScript object that can wrap other objects.
- A Proxy lets you control operations on other objects.
- 💡A Proxy can trap and intercept code when someone is:
    👉 Reading a property (get)
    👉 Setting a property (set)
    👉 Deleting a property (deleteProperty)
    👉 Checking if a property exists (has)
    👉 Calling a function (apply)
    👉 Constructing an object (construct)

- 💡💡A Proxy lets you run your own code when someone interacts with an object.
- 💡💡A Proxy Can be a middleman between your code and a JavaScript object.
- Proxy Syntax:
    const proxy = new Proxy(target, handler);
    
    -> target - the original object or function
    -> handler - an object with trap methods

- eg:   const myObject = {name: "Jan"};

        const proxy = new Proxy(myObject, {
            get(target, prop) {
                return target[prop];
            }
        });


#) Proxy Logging:
    - A typical Proxy example is logging of object changes.
    - Below is a demo that:
        👉 Wraps an object in a Proxy
        👉 Logs whenever a property is read or written
        👉 Logs each get and set operation in real time

        <script>
            const user = {
                name: "John",
                age: 40
            };

            const proxy = new Proxy(user, {
                get(target, property) {
                    log("Getting: " + property);
                    return target[property];
                },

                set(target, property, value) {
                    log("Setting: " + property);
                    return target[property];
                }
            });

            function log(message) {
                const time = new Date().toLocaleTimeString();
                document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML += `[${time}] ${message} <br>`
            }

            proxy.name = "John";
            proxy.age = 42;

            let text1 = proxy.name;
            let text2 = proxy.age;
        </script>

        o/p:    [10:12:33 AM] Setting: name
                [10:12:33 AM] Setting: age
                [10:12:33 AM] Getting: name
                [10:12:33 AM] Getting: age



#) Proxy with Reflect (Most Common):
    - Below is a demo that:
        👉 Wraps an object in a Proxy
        👉 Logs whenever a property is read or written
        👉 Uses Reflect.get() and Reflect.set() inside the Proxy handlers
        👉 get trap uses Reflect.get(target, property, receiver)
        👉 set trap uses Reflect.set(target, property, value, receiver)
        👉 Reflect makes the Proxy behavior match the normal object behavior

        <script>
            const user = {
                name: "John",
                age: 30
            };

            const proxy = new Proxy(user, {
                get(target, property) {
                    log("Getting: " + property); 
                    // Safe forwarding with Reflect
                    return Reflect.get(target, property);
                },

                set(target, property, value) {
                    log("Setting: " + property);    
                    // Safe forwarding with Reflect
                    return Reflect.set(target, property, value);
                }
            });

            function log(message) {
                const time = new Date().toLocaleTimeString();
                document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML += `[${time}] ${message} <br>`
            }

            proxy.name = "John";
            proxy.age = 42;

            let text1 = proxy.name;
            let text2 = proxy.age;
        </script>

        o/p:    [11:44:23 AM] Setting: name
                [11:44:23 AM] Setting: age
                [11:44:23 AM] Getting: name
                [11:44:23 AM] Getting: age



#) Proxy with Reflect Flow:
    - The flow below is the essence of JavaScript metaprogramming with Proxy + Reflect.
                                            
                                Your JavaScript
                            (reading/writing obj)
                                    |
                                    |
                                    v
                                    Proxy
                            (intercepts action)
                                |           |
                                |           | (trap (get, set, ....))
                                |           |
                                |           v
                                |        Your Code
                                | (logging, validation, reactivity)
                                |           |
                                |           |
                                v           v
                                    Reflect
                        (forwards operation correctly)
                                        |
                                        |
                                        v
                            Target Object/ Real Operation
    
    - Flow Explanation:
        👉 Your code interacts with an object
        👉 Proxy intercepts the operation
        👉 Your trap code decides what to do
        👉 Reflect forwards the operation safely
        👉 The target object receives the real action



#) Why Proxies?
    - Proxies allow you to:
        👉 Add logging
        👉 Validate changes
        👉 Auto-generate properties
        👉 Protect sensitive data
        👉 Create virtual or computed objects
        👉 Intercept function calls
        👉 Create reactive systems (like Vue.js)



#) Proxy Validation:

        <script>
            user = {
                name: "Johnny",
                age: 45
            };

            const proxy = new Proxy(user, {
                set(target, prop, value) {
                    if(prop === "age" && value < 0) {
                        text = "Age cannot be negative!";
                        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = text;
                    }
                    return Reflect.set(target, prop, value);
                }
            });

            proxy.age = 50; // OK
            proxy.age = -5; // Error
        </script>



#) Virtual Properties:

        <script>
            const person = {
                first: "John",
                last: "Doe"
            };

            const virtual = new Proxy(person, {
                get(target, prop) {
                    if(prop === "fullName") {
                        return target.first + " " + target.last;
                    }
                    return Reflect.get(target, prop);
                }
            });

            let text = virtual.fullName // John Doe
            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = text;
        </script>



#) Dynamic Functions:

        <script>
            const fn = new Function("a", "b", "return a + b");
            let result = fn(3, 2);

            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result + "<br>";

            // -------------------------- another example -----------------------------------------------------

            function buildOperation(operation) {
                return new Function("a", "b", `return a ${operation} b`);
            }

            const op = "*";
            const func = buildOperation(op);

            let result1 = func(3, 2);

            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML += result1;
        </script>
    
    - Metaprogramming lets JavaScript:
        Intercept behavior
        Modify behavior
        Define new behavior
        Generate behavior dynamically
        It gives developers deep control over the language's inner workings.



#) Proxy Traps:
    - 💡A trap is a function inside a Proxy handler.
    - 💡It runs whenever a specific operation is performed on the Proxy.
    - Below is a complete and accurate explanation of every JavaScript Proxy trap, what triggers them, their
        parameters, and what they are expected to return.

                Trap Name	                Triggered when
            -------------------------------------------------------------------------
                get	                        A property is read
                set	                        A property is changed
                has	                        Using the in operator
                deleteProperty	            A property is deleted
                apply	                    A function is called
                construct	                An object is cretated (with new)
                getOwnPropertyDescriptor	A property descriptor is retrieved
                defineProperty	            A property is defined
                getPrototypeOf	            A prototype is retrieved
                setPrototypeOf	            A prototype is set
                isExtensible	            Extensibility is checked
                preventExtensions	        Existenibility is prevented
                ownKeys	                    Properties are listed
        
        -> The list above is 2025-accurate and includes all 13 Proxy traps defined in ECMAScript.
        -> Each trap handler is decribed below.
    

    1) handler.get():
        - Triggered when a property is read:

            get(obj, prop, receiver) {
                return Reflect.get(obj, prop, receiver);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object
            👉 prop - the property being accessed
            👉 receiver - the this value for getters (usually the proxy itself)

        - Triggered by:
            👉 proxy.property
            👉 proxy["property"]
            👉 object.property()
        
        - Must Return
            👉 The property value
    

    2) handler.set():
        - Triggered when a property is changed:

            set(obj, prop, value, receiver) {
                return Reflect.set(obj, prop, value, receiver);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object
            👉 prop - the property being set
            👉 value - the new value for the property
            👉 receiver - the this value for setters (usually the proxy itself)

        - Triggered by:
            👉 proxy.property = value
            👉 proxy["property"] = value
        
        - Must Return
            👉 true if the assignment succeeded, false otherwise
    

    3) handler.has():
        - Triggered when using the in operator:

            has(obj, prop) {
                return Reflect.has(obj, prop);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object
            👉 prop - the property being checked

        - Triggered by:
            👉 "property" in proxy
        
        - Must Return
            👉 true if the property exists, false otherwise
    

    4) handler.deleteProperty():
        - Triggered when a property is deleted:

            deleteProperty(obj, prop) {
                return Reflect.deleteProperty(obj, prop);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object
            👉 prop - the property being deleted

        - Triggered by:
            👉 delete proxy.property
        
        - Must Return
            👉 true if the property was successfully deleted, false otherwise
    

    5) handler.apply():
        - Triggered when a function is called:

            apply(func, thisArg, argumentsList) {
                return Reflect.apply(func, thisArg, argumentsList);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 func - the target function
            👉 thisArg - the this value for the function call
            👉 argumentsList - an array of arguments for the function call

        - Triggered by:
            👉 proxy()
            👉 proxy.call()
            👉 proxy.apply()
        
        - Must Return
            👉 The return value of the function


    6) handler.construct():
        - Triggered when an object is created with new:

            construct(obj, argumentsList, newTarget) {
                return Reflect.construct(obj, argumentsList, newTarget);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target constructor object
            👉 argumentsList - an array of arguments for the constructor
            👉 newTarget - the constructor that was directly invoked (usually the proxy itself)

        - Triggered by:
            👉 new proxy()
        
        - Must Return
            👉 An object created by the constructor(the new instance)
    

    7) handler.getOwnPropertyDescriptor():
        - Triggered when a property descriptor is retrieved:

            getOwnPropertyDescriptor(obj, prop) {
                return Reflect.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(obj, prop);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object
            👉 prop - the property whose descriptor is being retrieved

        - Triggered by:
            👉 Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(obj, prop)
        
        - Must Return
            👉 A property descriptor object or undefined if the property does not exist
    

    8) handler.defineProperty():
        - Triggered when a property is defined:

            defineProperty(obj, prop, descriptor) {
                return Reflect.defineProperty(obj, prop, descriptor);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object
            👉 prop - the property being defined
            👉 descriptor - a property descriptor

        - Triggered by:
            👉 Object.defineProperty()
        
        - Must Return
            👉 true if the property was successfully defined, false otherwise
    

    9) handler.getPrototypeOf():
        - Triggered when a prototype is retrieved:

            getPrototypeOf(obj) {
                return Reflect.getPrototypeOf(obj);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object

        - Triggered by:
            👉 Object.getPrototypeOf()
        
        - Must Return
            👉 An Object or null
    

    10) handler.setPrototypeOf():
        - Triggered when a prototype is set:

            setPrototypeOf(obj, proto) {
                return Reflect.setPrototypeOf(obj, proto);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object
            👉 proto - the new prototype object or null

        - Triggered by:
            👉 Object.setPrototypeOf()
        
        - Must Return
            👉 true if the prototype was successfully set, false otherwise
    

    11) handler.isExtensible():
        - Triggered when extensibility is checked:

            isExtensible(obj) {
                return Reflect.isExtensible(obj);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object

        - Triggered by:
            👉 Object.isExtensible()
        
        - Must Return
            👉 true if the object is extensible, false otherwise
    

    12) handler.preventExtensions():
        - Triggered when extensibility is prevented:

            preventExtensions(obj) {
                return Reflect.preventExtensions(obj);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object

        - Triggered by:
            👉 Object.preventExtensions()
        
        - Must Return
            👉 true if the object was successfully made non-extensible, false otherwise
    

    13) handler.ownKeys():
        - Triggered when properties are listed (property names or symbols):

            ownKeys(obj) {
                return Reflect.ownKeys(obj);
            }
        
        - Parameters
            👉 obj - the target object

        - Triggered by:
            👉 Object.getOwnPropertyNames()
            👉 Object.getOwnPropertySymbols()
            👉 Object.keys()
        
        - Must Return
            👉 An array of property keys (strings and symbols) with no duplicates



#) Proxy Traps Map Reflect Methods:
    - A Proxy trap represents one of JavaScript's internal operations:
        [[Construct]]
        [[Call]]
        [[Get]]
        [[Set]]
        [[HasProperty]]
        [[Delete]]
        [[DefineProperty]]
        [[GetOwnProperty]]
        [[OwnPropertyKeys]]
        [[GetPrototypeOf]]
        [[SetPrototypeOf]]
        [[PreventExtensions]]
        [[IsExtensible]]
        
    - These internal operations are what JavaScript uses (inside the engine) when you access or modify objects.
    - When a Proxy intercepts one of these operations, they should be forwarded correctly:

            get(target, property, receiver) {
                return Reflect.get(target, property, receiver);
            }

        -> Reflect is used because Reflect methods are 1-to-1 mirrors of the internal operations.
            👉 They produce correct return values (true/false/descriptor)
            👉 They avoid throwing errors that would break Proxy rules
            👉 They make the Proxy behave like normal JavaScript objects (unless modified)
            👉 This is why every Proxy trap has a Reflect method with the same name and signature.



#) JavaScript Internals Became Reflect:
    - Before ES6 (2015), many fundamental operations did not exist as functions:

        Operation	        Before E6	                        Problem
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        get property	    obj[prop]	                        Not callable as a function
        set property	    obj[prop] = value	                Not callable as a function
        delete property	    delete obj[prop]	                Operator, not a function
        check property	    "prop" in obj	                    Operator, not a function
        construct (new)	    new Foo()	                        Not callable generically
        get prototypes	    Object.getPrototypeOf(obj)	        Throws on non-objects
        define property	    Object.defineProperty()         	Returns object instead of boolean
        own keys	        Object.keys()	                    Not complete (misses symbols)
    
    - These were incomplete and inconsistent for Proxy forwarding.
    - So ES6 (2015) added Reflect:

            Internal Operation	            Reflect Method
        ---------------------------------------------------------------------
            [[Construct]]	                Reflect.construct()
            [[Call]]	                    Reflect.apply()
            [[Get]]	                        Reflect.get()
            [[Set]]	                        Reflect.set()
            [[HasProperty]]	                Reflect.has()
            [[Delete]]	                    Reflect.deleteProperty()
            [[DefineProperty]]	            Reflect.defineProperty()
            [[GetOwnProperty]]	            Reflect.getOwnProperty()
            [[OwnPropertyKeys]]	            Reflect.ownPropertyKeys()
            [[IsExstensible]]	            Reflect.isExtensible()
            [[PreventExstensions]]	        Reflect.preventExtensions()
            [[GetPrototypeOf]]	            Reflect.getPrototypeOf()
            [[SetPrototypeOf]]	            Reflect.setPrototypeOf()